question: What can you catch but cannot throw?
Pick me up and scratch my head. I’ll turn red and then black. What am I?
I have a neck, but I don’t have a head, and I wear a cap. What am I?
Cut me and I won’t cry, but you will. What am I?
Of the options below, what has four legs, one head and one foot?
What runs around a house but does not move?
I can’t be seen, but I can be heard. I won’t answer until spoken to. What am I?
What has 13 hearts, but no other organ?
In a house, what room do ghosts avoid?
I am a mother's child and a father's child but nobody's son. Who am I?
Adriana's mom had four kids: Marta, Anna, Justina…
What has a head and a tail but no body?
I last forever and you might have too much or too little of me, either way you will run out of me eventually. What am I?
What goes up, but never goes down?
I am not alive, but I grow; I don't have lungs, but I need air; I don't have a mouth, but I need water to live. What am I?
I can be cracked, made, told, and played. What am I?
I am always hungry, I must always be fed. The finger I touch, will soon turn red. What am I?
I am a word that starts with a letter "t", ends with a letter "t", and has "t" in the middle. What am I?
I am always in front of you, but you can never see me. What am I?
What has a bottom at the top?
What is full of holes but still holds water?
What is so fragile that saying its name breaks it?
What has a bed but never sleeps, a mouth but never eats, and a bank but never lends money?
What has a thumb and four fingers but is not alive?
What has a hundred eyes but cannot see?
What goes through cities and fields, but never moves?
I have cities, but no houses. I have mountains, but no trees. I have water, but no fish. What am I?
There is one in every corner and two in every room.
I have one eye. See near and far. I hold the moments you treasure and the things that make you weep.
A house with two occupants, sometimes one, rarely three. Break the walls, eat the boarders, then throw away me.
I come in winter. I cannot see, hear, or feel. I can't eat, But you can eat parts of me.
I cant speak or hear and yet I always tell the truth. What am I?
Many times, you need me. The more and more you take me further, the more and more you leave me behind. What am I?
The one who makes me does not need me, when he makes me. The one who buys me does not use me for himself or herself. The one who uses me doesn’t know that he or she is using me. What am I?
I don’t have money, though I do have banks. I feed others, though I don’t eat. Cross me if you can, I won’t be mad. What am I?

Take away my first letter, and I still sound the same. Take away my last letter, I still sound the same. Even take away my letter in the middle, I will still sound the same. I am a five-letter word. What am I?
I have no bones and no legs, but if you keep me warm, I will soon walk away. What am I?
I am always on the dinner table, but you don’t get to eat me. What am I?
I am often following you and copying your every move, yet you can never touch me or catch me. What am I?
With pointed fangs I sit and wait; with piercing force I crunch out fate; grabbing victims, proclaiming might; physically joining with a single bite. What am I?
People have stepped on me, but not many. I never stay full for long. I have a dark side. What am I?
I am always running, but never get tired or hot. What am I?
I have a head much smaller than my long neck. People who play with me pick at me and that’s fine. What am I?
If you take away one hand, some will remain. What am I?
Halo of water, tongue of wood, walls of stone, long have I stood. What am I?
People make me, save me, change me, raise me. What am I?
The shorter I am, the bigger I am. What am I?
I make a loud sound when I’m changing. When I do change, I get bigger, but I weigh less.
It can be said: to be gold is to be good; to be stone is to be nothing; to be glass is to be fragile; to be cold is to be cruel.
I have keys, but no locks. I have space, but no room. You can enter, but can’t go inside.
I am the only vegetable that is never sold frozen, canned, processed, cooked, or in any other form but fresh.
My first is in chocolate, but not in ham. My second is in cake and also in jam. My third at tea-time is easily found. My whole is a friend who’s often around.
I add lots of flavor and have many layers, but if you get too close, I’ll make you cry.
I don’t have eyes, ears, nose, and tongue, but I can see, smell, hear, and taste everything.
I am a word of five letters and people eat me. If you remove the first letter, I become a form of energy. Remove the first two and I’m needed to live. Scramble the last three and you can drink me.
It’s good to stretch me and push my limits. The more you use me, the stronger I get. When I am sharp, I’m at my best.
I run, but I don’t walk. I drip and drop, but I can’t pick myself up. You have to consume me and sometimes I surround you.
I sound like I could cut you, but I’m actually quite comfortable. I can be green or yellow. I can be stiff or soft. I am a friend to bugs and also bare feet.
I have a stem, but I am not a flower. I have a foot, but I cannot hop. Children are too young to hold me.

I can be open or closed, or big or small. I can reveal the truth or hide it. I am almost always welcome and can spring up unannounced. Everyone has one, but not everyone shares. Laughter comes after me.
I am round as a sphere, but then you make me something else. I am one hundred yards long, or even longer.
You can touch me, but I can’t touch you back. You can see me, but I only reflect you and can never reject you.
Half of me will mend, the other half will imprison. When I am together, I will poison. Who am I?
Our dinner guests cry that we are evil, when they notice their place in the meal. But it’s no big deal. We are just one big happy tribe that gets real fed up with people! Who are we?
A man who lives in New York legally married three women. He did not get a divorce, an annulment, or legally separate. Who is he?
My first four letters describe all living things. My last five letters are another word for knight. My job is to save you, and I’m a fan of water. Who am I?
I craft crowns of gold and bridges of silver. Who am I?

I carry a lot of secrets, happy or sad. I drive or walk to my destination rain or shine to make sure I give you what is truly yours. Everything that I bring with me is destined for only for one place which is decided in advance. Who am I?

I can help a minor, I can help a senior. I can take care of you, and no matter what your mood is, I always give you a happy face. I probably won’t give you any advice, but I am always grateful when you give me tips. Who am I?
I wash, cut, and shave a dozen times a day yet I still have lots of hair. Who am I?
Sometimes you are relieved to see me, and other times you run from me in fear. Sometimes I stop you and sometimes I let you go, but whenever you need me, I am always a quick call away. Who am I?
I am small, have wings, and carry a weapon. I target people and once I do, they’re usually glad I did. February is the month in which I appear the most. Who am I?
I have wings and a wand. When you lose something and leave it under your pillow, I leave you a prize. Who am I?
I grew up outside society. I am wild, my voice echoes throughout the jungle, and nature is my playground. Who am I?
What can you break, even if you never pick it up or touch it?
I have branches, but no fruit, trunk or leaves. What am I?
What can you catch, but not throw?
What has to be broken before you can use it?
I’m tall when I’m young, and I’m short when I’m old. What am I?
What goes up but never comes down?
The more of this there is, the less you see. What is it?
What can travel all around the world without leaving its corner?
What question can you never answer yes to?
What is so fragile that saying its name breaks it?
What has 13 hearts, but no other organs?
What can run but never walks, has a mouth but never talks, has a head but never weeps, has a bed but never sleeps?
What can fill a room but takes up no space?
What has one eye, but can’t see?
If you drop me I’m sure to crack, but give me a smile and I’ll always smile back. What am I?
The more you take, the more you leave behind. What are they?
What breaks yet never falls, and what falls yet never breaks?
I am always hungry and will die if not fed, but whatever I touch will soon turn red. What am I?
What has one head, one foot and four legs?
The person who makes it has no need of it; the person who buys it has no use for it. The person who uses it can neither see nor feel it. What is it?
I have lakes with no water, mountains with no stone and cities with no buildings. What am I?
What has a head, a tail, is brown, and has no legs?
Can you name three consecutive days without using the words Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday, or Sunday?
What begins with an “e” and only contains one letter?
What belongs to you, but other people use it more than you?
What can point in every direction but can't reach the destination by itself.
What has many keys, but can't even open a single door?
A man rode out of town on Sunday, he stayed a whole night at a hotel and rode back to town the next day on Sunday. How is this possible?
What has six faces, but does not wear makeup, has twenty-one eyes, but cannot see? What is it?
This is as light as a feather, yet no man can hold it for long. What am I?
What runs around the whole yard without moving?
The more you take away, the more I become. What am I?
I have two hands, but I can not scratch myself. What am I?
Poor people have it. Rich people need it. If you eat it you die. what is it?
What goes up when the rain comes down?
